39","1204":"1204","1257":"1257","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","about 1235":"about 1235","ABT    1280":"about 1280","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Breigan,Llansanwyr,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hywel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywell","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"\"Sais\"","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fernando, Orlando, Angelita, Arturo, Delfina, Desiderio, Dionicio, Edgardo, Elva, Fidel, Isidoro, Jere.","Catalan: topographic name from <i>saix</i> ‘rock’ (from Latin <i>saxum</i>), or an ethnic name for a Saxon, derived from the root of <i>saxó</i> ‘Saxon’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hywel \"Sais\" ap Hywel was born about 1235, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Hywel 'Dew' ap Cadwgon, was 32 and his mother, Betyn Norris, was 26. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Hywel Sais ap Hywel."},"et":{"about 1235–":"umbes 1235–Surnud","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1257–Male":"1257–Surnud","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1239–Female":"1239–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1204–1320":"1204–1320","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","ABT    1275":"umbes 1275","1275":"1275","1440":"1440","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1239":"1239","1204":"1204","1257":"1257","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","about 1235":"umbes 1235","ABT    1280":"umbes 1280","Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Breigan,Llansanwyr,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","{Blddn ap Mnrch}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1235–":"noin 1235–Kuollut","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","124